en: Cushing Memorial Library was built in 1930 and cost $225,000. It was the first freestanding library on campus. It is named after E.B. Cushing, Class of 1880, former President of the Texas A&M Board of Directors.

All Faiths Chapel was built in 1957. A gift of the Association of Former Students, it was designed by professor emeritus Richard 'Dik' Vrooman, '52 when he was an assistant professor in the Divison of Architecture. The design was selected as a winner in a competion sponsored by the Association open only to graduates of the Texas A&M Division of Architecture.

Fish Pond was completed in 1940 as a class gift from the class of '38. It was refurbished by the class of 1977 in 1975. In 2011, Fish Pond was relocated across the street from its original location, placing it directly in front of Sbisa Dining Hall.
The original Zachry Building was built in 1972 at a cost of 324,400. The update to the Zachry was completed in 2018.
Foster Hall was erected in 1899 and razed in 1951. This building cost $28,000 to build. It was built as a dormitory and named for Lafayette Lumpkin Foster, former Texas A&M President (1898-1901).
Hotard Hall was originally built in 1939 to house food service personnel. Hotard became a dormitory in 1958. In 2004, Hotard Hall became office spaces.

The Sink Building was erected circa 1885 and razed circa 1900. This building was located where Cushing Memorial Library is now. The Sink was the "first major effort of the college to furnish adequate toilet facilities for the student body"
Keathley Hall is a dormitory that was built in 1964. It is named for Medal of Honor recipient Staff Sergeant George Dennis Keathley, class of 1937.
Wisenbaker Engineering Building was erected in 1983 at a cost of $177,704.
The Joe C. Richardson, Jr. Petroleum Engineering Building was built in 1990 and still stands.

The Computing Services Building was constructed in 1959. The building was one of the first in the nation designed to house computers and utilized special air-conditioning and humidity control features. It was home to an IBM-704 high-speed electronic computer when first opened.
Olin E. Teague Research Center was built in 1966 at a cost of $63,515.
Rudder Tower was erected in 1973 at a cost of $302,240. Rudder Tower and Theater is a 12 story conference tower with a theatre complex.
The Hensel Terrace was built in 1960 and razed 2011. This residential development served as married student housing.
The 1891 President's House was built in 1891 and burned on January 26, 1963. Also known as Prexy's House.
This later assembly hall was erected in 1923 and razed in 1953. It seated 2000 and included a stage and dressing rooms. It was frame construction with a stucco exterior treatment.
In 1912, construction of Sbisa Hall began at a cost of $205,000.
The News Stand stood from circa 1919 to circa 1945.

Francis Hall was erected in 1918. This building was also known as the Veterinary Science Building. It was heavily renovated in 2015 and is now home to the Construction Science Department. It still has a ramp at the rear that was used when leading livestock into the building.
The Doherty Building was erected in 1960. Named for Wilfred Doherty, class of 1922, former president of the Board of Regents (1955-59). Originally built to house the Petroleum Engineering Department.
The Peterson Building was erected in 1963 at a cost of $84,831.

Cain Pool, an Olympic-sized outdoor swimming pool, was built in 1962 and razed in 1997 for the expansion of Kyle Field. The pool was named for R. Wofford Cain '13, member of the Board of Regents 1966-1971.
Walton Hall was erected in 1931 at a cost of $250,000.

The Gibb Gilchrist Engineering Library was built in 1952. It was demolished in 1968, but small portions were left intact and incorporated into Sterling C. Evans Library. It was named after former Texas A&M President Gibb Gilchrist.

Military Walk began as a dirt path in the 1880s, but was used by Cadets transiting between Sbisa and Guion Hall after Guion was built in 1918. It was revitalized and restored in 2010 with the help of funding from Dan A. Hughes, class of 1951.
The Hospital was erected in 1916 at a cost of $58,000. This building was also known as the Northside Laundry and Special Services Building.
The Nuclear Science Center was completed in 1961. The reactor in this facility was first taken critical on December 18, 1961.
The Olsen Field at Bluebell Park was erected in 1979 at a cost of $60,537.
Heldenfels Hall was built in 1977. It is named for Hugo C. "Tony" Heldenfels, '35, former president of the Board of Regents.
Mosher Hall was built in 1976. It is named after Edward J. Mosher, class of 1928, a former Texas A&M football player and member of the executive board of the Former Students Association.

The Infirmary was erected in 1895 for a cost of $4,000. The Infirmary originally stood where Francis Hall is now, but was moved 500 feet away in 1918 and used for apartments until finally being razed in 1932.
The Reed House was built in 1984, also known as Chancellor's House and One Reed Drive.
Fermier Hall was built in 1919. This building was originally known as the Mechanical Engineering Building. When built, it included twin steeples that have since been removed.

The Animal Industries Building was built in 1932 at a cost of $222,738.76. It was designed by S.C.P. Vosper and dedicated to "Pioneer Livestock Men of Texas". For many years it housed laboratories where students learned to butcher and process meat. It is now known as the AI Engineering Building and is home to the Department of Nuclear Engineering.

Engineering Activities Building B was built in 1949 at a cost of $65,000. Engineering Activities Building A and C were built in 1954. Originally named the Beasley Laboratory, it was used for cotton research and housed a genetics laboratory, a seed storage and general work room and a potting room. It included two greenhouses with a total of 4,590 squre feet to allow year-round study of live cotton plants.

The Albritton Bell Tower was constructed in 1984. It was a gift of Martha and Ford D. Albritton '43. It is 138 feet tall, has 49 bells that can be played from a keyboard, and includes a time capsule to be opened at the Texas A&M Bicentennial in 2076. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mJpLS0O5ckM&t=193s
Science Hall was erected in 1900 at a cost of $31,000 and razed in 1963. This building was originally known as the Agricultural Building but later known as the Science Hall.

One-room cottages called Hollywood Shacks were erected at a cost $43,000. They replaced tent dwellings that had been in use since 1906. The "shacks" were relocated slightly west of their original location when Puryear and Law Halls were built on the site in 1928. They were finally hauled away in 1932.

Bizzell Hall was erected in 1918 at a cost of $90,862.74 and demolished in 2017. Designed by College Architect Rolland Adelsperger, it was originally built as a dormitory and later used to house various offices. It was named in honor of W. B. Bizzell, president of the College from 1914 to 1925.
The historic Northgate Station post office was constructed from 1936-7 with federal Treasury Department funds. The building, which housed an example of New Deal artwork, is still in service.
The Boyett Store was originally built around 1880 by William C. Boyett. In the 1930s, the Boyett Store was relocated to the Northgate area

The Reynolds Medical Science Building was built in 1983. It is named for Joe H. Reynolds, who served as a marine in WWII and Korea and was a member of the Texas A&M University System Board of Regents from 1973-81 and 1983-89.
The Student Recreation Center was erected in 1995 at a cost of $334,642.

Gathright Hall was completed in September of 1876 at a cost of $38,000. Named for the first president of Texas A&M, Thomas Gathright, it was also known as the Mess Hall and Steward's Hall. It was demolished in 1933.
The Highway Research Center was built in 1954 and was demolished in 1988 to build the Joe C. Richardson Petroleum Engineering Building.
The Beef Cattle Center was built in 1950 at a cost of $110,000 and razed in 1991.

Halbouty was built in 1932. This building was originally known as the Petroleum Engineering Experiment Station and Geology Building. The building originally featured a central tower concealing a water tank. The tower was removed in 1972 because cast stone facings on it had worked loose for a number of years and posed a danger should they fall. The building was renamed in 1977 for Texas petroleum engineer and geologist Michael T. Halbouty, class of 1930.
Fountain Hall was erected in 1939 as one of the group of 12 dormitories that are now known as the Corps Dorms.

The Corps Dormitories include twelve dormitory buildings erected in 1939. Included are Briggs, Fountain, Gainer, H.H. Harrington, Kiest, Lacy, Spence, Leonard (originally Schumacher), Harrell (originally McInnis), Whiteley (originally White), White, and Utay Halls.
The YMCA was erected in 1914 at a cost of $120,000.
The Veterinary Anatomy Lab was erected in 1932 apart of a Veterinary Medicine Group Buildings at a cost of $200,000.
Rosenthal Meat Science Center and Technology
The Rosenthal Meat Sciences & Technology Center was built in 1983.
The Reed-McDonald Building was erected in 1967. First known as the "Services Building", it was re-dedicated in 1973 to Reed McDonald, first director of the State Feed and Fertilizer Control Service.
The Biological Sciences Building was originally built in 1950 at a cost of $602,477.44. An addition was completed in 1967.

Faculty housing was originally built in September of 1876, starting with 5 professors' residences at a cost of  $3,000 each. The original housing along Throckmorton Street became known as "Quality Row." Over time three of the original five brick homes were demolished and replaced with frame homes, and all were removed in 1948 to make way for a park. The area is now part of Aggie Park.

Kiest Hall, also known as Dorm 2, was built in 1939. It is named for Edwin J. Kiest, former editor, publisher, and owner of the Dallas Times-Herald and member of the Texas A&M Board of Directors from 1927-1941.

The Minnie Belle and Herman F. Heep '20 Center was erected in 1977. It is also known as the Soil Crop Sciences and Entomology Center. Hermann Heep was a member of the Board of Directors from 1957-1960. His wife Minnie Belle Heep continued to support the Texas A&M Foundation for decades after her husband's death.
The Horticulture Forest Science Building was built in 1984.
Schuhmacher Hall was built in 1966 at a cost of $38,957.
The Williams Alumni Center was built in 1987 and is the headquarters of the Association of Former Students.  It is named after Clayton W. Williams Jr. '54.

G. Rollie White Coliseum was built in 1954 and razed in 2013. Named for G. Rollie White, class of 1895 and member of the Board of Directors (1926-55). The Coliseum was host to countless basketball games, volleyball tournaments, concerts, and graduations during its almost 60-year lifespan.

Old Main was built in September 1876 at an original cost of $100,000. It was built of brick made from local clay that was fired on site. It was destroyed by fire in 1912. After it burned, the remaining walls were pulled down by students with ropes following artillery barrages, rifle fire, and dynamite charges. The Academic Building building now stands on the site previously occupied by Old Main.
The Old Music Hall was built in 1920 and razed in 1964. The Music Hall was the original A&M Consolidated High School until 1935.
Anthropology, Plant Sciences and Agricultural Economics Research Lab
The Luedecke Building was erected in 1966. It is home to the Cyclotron Institute. It was renamed in 1994 after Major General Alvin R. Luedecke, class of 1932.

The Coke Building was built in 1951 to house the administrative offices of the College. It is named in honor of Richard Coke, Governor and first chairman of the Texas A&M Board of Directors. Coke gave an address at the opening of the College on October 4, 1876, quotations from which are engraved in a marble memorial tablet in the lobby.

Hart Hall was erected in 1930 on the site of the 1889 Assembly Hall (also known as the Armory and the Chapel). The cornerstone of the old Assembly Hall remains incorporated into the newer dormitory building. Hart Hall is named after Lawrence J. Hart, president of the Texas A&M Board of Directors from 1919-25.

The Dwight Look Building was built in 1985 and was formerly known as the CE/TTI Building. It incorporates two cast stone pig's heads and sections of ornamental frieze from the Veterinary Anatomy Building that formerly occupied the site.

Langford Architecture Center Buildings A&B were built in 1977 to accompany the original Architecture Building completed in 1963. The complex is named for Ernest Langford, class of 1913. Langford was head of the Division of Architecture 1929-56 and was a founding father of College Station and served as its mayor from 1942-1965. He also served as University Archivist 1957-1975.

The Memorial Student Center was built in 1950 and officially dedicated on April 21, 1951 to A&M students who died in World War II. It was rededicated in 1976 to Aggies who have died in all past, present, and future wars. It has undergone considerable expansion and renovation since it was built, with a major renovation occuring between 2009-12.
The Adams Band Hall was built in 1970 at a cost of 55,248.
The H.R. Bright Building was erected in 1989. It is named after Harvey R. Bright '43, chairman of the Board of Regents from 1981 to 1985.
This Veterinary Hospital was built in 1908 and razed circa 1932.

The Bell Building was built in 1942 at a cost of $293, 285.82 and razed 2014. An office building, it was only the second building on campus after Austin Hall to be oriented with the compass, facing almost due west. Originally built to house the state offices of the Agricultural Adjustment Administration, it later housed various agencies of the U. S. Department of Agriculture.

Mount Aggie was first constructed in 1977 across the street from East Kyle Field. In 1990, Mount Aggie was moved South of Kyle Field on Wellborn Road. In 1999, Mount Aggie was moved to West Campus, near the Omar Smith Instructional Tennis Center, where it currently still stands.

Cain Hall was built in 1975 as an athletics dormitory. It was later used for residence life administrative offices, Student Counseling Services, and general office space. It was neamed for R. Wofford Cain '13, a member of the Board of Regents 1966-71. It was demolished in 2015.
Married Student Apartments were built circa 1938 and razed 1988.

Mitchell Hall was erected in 1912 at a cost of $75,000 and razed in 1972. This building was located where Beutel Health Center is now. It was named for Harvey Mitchell who was known as the "Father of Brazos County" and was instrumental in the effort to secure Brazos County as the home of Texas A&M.

The horse barn was erected in 1932 as part of a veterinary medicine group of buildings. It was topped by two notable weather vanes, one depicting a cowboy on a bucking horse and the other a cowboy twirling a lasso.
The original Zachry Building was built in 1972 at a cost of 324,400. The update to the Zachry was completed in 2018.

Butler Hall was erected in 1918 at a cost of $90,000. This building was originally designed to house the administrative offices of the Agricultural Experiment Station. It was renamed in the 1980s to honor Eugene Butler, former editor of Progressive Farmer and a voice for policies supporting rural farming in Texas.

The Mechanical Engineering Office Building and the James J. Cain '51 Building were erected in 1986. These buildings are also known as the Engineering Physics Building. It was named for James J. Cain, class of 1951.

The DeWare Field House was built in 1924 and razed in 1997. This was the first dedicated gymnasium on campus. Named for Charles DeWare, class of 1909, A&M football player and president of the Association of Fomer Students.

The Chemistry and Veterinary Science Building was built in 1902 and razed in 1929. This building cost $31,000 and stood where Cushing Memorial Library is now. It included a central fan-forced ventilation system that could execute a complete air change of the building in under three minutes. There is a plaque denoting the former location of this building in the lawn in front of Cushing Memorial Library.

Goodwin Hall was built in 1908 and razed 1989. This building cost $53,500. It was built and used as a dormitory for its entire lifespan. It was named for George Iverson Goodwin, a Texas legislator who shepherded legislation that paved the way for the founding of Texas A&M.
Austin Hall was built in 1888 and razed in 1955. This building cost $11,000. It was the first campus bulding to oriented with compass, with its front elevation facing due south.
The Century Tree was planted in 1891 and still stands on campus today.

Bolton Hall, formerly known as the Electrical Engineering Building, was erected in 1912 at a cost of $75,000. Designed by College Architect F. E. Giesecke, it was later named in honor of Frank. C. Bolton, who served as President of the College from 1948-50. It was from Bolton Hall that the first play-by-play reporting of a football game in history was broadcast via radio using Morse code and series of abbreviations in 1921.

The Assembly Hall was built in 1889 at a cost of $22,218.64 and razed in 1929. It was the fifth principal building erected on the A&M campus. This building also was known later as the chapel and finally as the armory. Architect was Eugene T. Heiner. The only remnant of this building is the cornerstone, which is now integrated into Hart Hall, the building that stands upon its former site.
The original depot was constructed in 1883. The building was replaced in 1900. The depot was razed in 1966.
George H. W. Bush Presidential Library
The George Bush Presidential Library & Museum was erected in 1997.
The Jack K. Williams Administration Building was built in 1932. This building cost 353,000 dollars.

The construction for the Chemistry Building began in 1929 and was completed in 1933. This building cost $401,853.97 and exhibits the distinctive design work of S.C.P. Vosper. A wing was added in 1958.
Ross Hall was erected in 1892 at a cost of $20,000 and razed in 1955.
The Old University Police Station was built circa 1940 as the American Legion Project House and became the Police Station in 1982. It was razed in 1997.
The President's House was originally built in 1965.
The Military Sciences Building was originally known as the Extension Service Building and was constructed in 1924. This building is also known as Trigon.

Bagley Hall, originally known as the Textile Engineering Building, was erected in 1904 and razed in 1972. This building cost $31,000 and the equipment cost $20,000. It included a complete sprinkler system for fire control. It was later named in honor of Mr. J. B. Bagley, professor emeritus of cotton marketing. Former Architecture Division Head and College Archivist Ernest Langford stated that "Functionally, it is the best building ever erected on the campus."
Thompson Hall was erected in 1922 at a cost of $150,000
The State Chemist Building was erected in 1909. It was originally built of red brick, was painted yellow-beige in later years to blend in better with surrounding buildings. It was demolished in 2020.
Downs Natatorium was built in 1932 and razed in 1997. It was named for P.L. "Pinkie" Downs, class of 1906, former member of the Board of Directors  (1923-32).
The Psychology Building was built in 1920 at a cost of $100,000. This building was originally known as the Physics Building.

The Anthropology Building was built in 1952. Originally, this building was home to the Dean of Engineering, the Aerospace Engineering Department, the Architecture Research Center, and Industrial Engineering Department. It now houses the Department of Anthropology, the Institute of Nautical Archaeology, the Center for Maritime Archaeology and Conservation, and the Center for the Study of the First Americans.
Evans Library was built in 1929 at a cost of $712,093.

The project houses,or cooperative housing was housing for students during and after the Great Depression. Students were required to bring milking cows and chickens and do their own cooking and cleaning. Project houses were approved in 1937.
Milner Hall was erected in 1911. Originally built as a dormitory, it was converted to classrooms and office space in 1976. It is named after Robert Teague Milner, president of TAMC from 1908-13.
The Pavilion was erected in 1917 at a cost of $56,000. This building was also known as the Animal Husbandry Pavilion.
Construction began in late 1943 and was estimated to have cost $50,000.
The Koldus Building was erected in 1992. It is named for John J. Koldus III, the first and longest-serving vice president for Student Affairs from 1973-1993.

Originally built as a serum laborator in 1917, this building became a museum from 1937-65 housing natural history and anthropological items, many of which had been collected by Dr. Mark Francis, first dean of the Texas A&M College of Veterinary Medicine. It also housed the mummy of Ankh-Hap, now in the Hosuton Museum of Natural Science. The museum was razed in 1972 to make way for Langford Architecture Center.
Moses Hall was completed in 1942. It is named after Captain Andrew Moses, Commandant of Cadets and professor of military science at Texas A&M from 1907-1911.

The Blocker Building was erected in 1981. Initally known as the Academic and Agency Building when it opened in 1981, it was dedicated in 1983 to John R. Blocker '45, former member of the Texas A&M University Board of Regents.

Haynes Engineering Building was built in 1932 as the Veterinary Hospital at a cost of $142,852.48. It was originally associated with three other smaller structures in its vicinity: a veterinary anatomy laboratory and two stables. After Veterinary Medicine moved to west campus, the Veterinary Hospital was repurposed and known for many years as the Civil Engineering Building.

Law and Puryear Halls were built in 1928 and razed in 1997. Law Hall was named for Francis Marion Law, class of 1895, president of the Board of Directors at Texas A&M University from 1924 to 1945. Puryear Hall was named for Charles Puryear, first Head of the Civil Engineering and Physics Department at Texas A&M College in 1889 and held this position of one year. Following which, Mr. Puryear held the position of head of mathematics for 42 years, was dean of the college for 25 years and acting president for one year.
Bachelor Hall and its associated buggy house were built in the 1890s. In 1924, Bachelor Hall was destroyed by fire, along with 3 businesses and the post office.

The Kleberg Center was built in 1978. It is named for Robert Justus Kleberg, Jr., former president and CEO of the King Ranch. It features a mounted statue of Kleberg in front of the building and is home to the Branded Staircase, which showcases almost 2500 brands of Texas ranches.
Duncan Dining Hall was constructed at the same time as the 12 Corps dormitories in 1939. It is named for Director of Subsistence William Duncan, who served in that role 1920-37.
The Veterinary Teaching Hospital was built in 1953.
Legett Hall as built in 1911 and is the oldest dormitory on campus. It is named for Judge Kirvin Kade Legett, president of the Board of Directors from 1907-1911.
Hughes Hall was built in 1966 at a cost of $38,957.
Easterwood Airport opened in May, 1940. It is named after U.S. Navy Lieutenant Jesse Easterwood, class of 1909, World War I combat aviator and recipient of the Navy Cross.

The Moore-Connally Building was erected in 1991. It serves as the state headquarters for the Texas A&M University System. It was constructed around the concrete framework of a building that had stood unfinished since the early- to mid-1980s. Originally named the John B. Connally Building, its name was changed to Moore-Connally in 2013.
Aston Hall is a dormitory building constructed in 1976.
The Oceanography & Meteorology Building was built in 1973. It is named after David Eller, class of 1959 and Chairman of the Board of Regents from 1983-89. It is the tallest building on campus.
The Board of Director's House was built in 1912 and destroyed by fire in 1979.
The carpenter shops were built circa 1877 and stood behind Old Main.
The Mechanical Engineering Shops were erected 1892 at a cost of $11,500. The Mechanical Shops were destroyed by fire in 1922.
The Beutel Health Center was built in 1974. The center is named after Albert P. Beutel, member of the Board of Directors from 1963 to 1969, and vice president from 1969 to 1974.
The Creamery was built in 1956 and razed 1995. Students, faculty, and campus visitors could buy freshly-made ice cream here for many years. The Central Campus Garage is now located on the site.
Pfeuffer Hall was built in 1887 at a cost of $11,500 and razed in 1954.

Nagle Hall was erected in 1909. This building was originally known as the Civil Engineering Building. It is currently the oldest building on campus and is named for James C. Nagle, the first dean of the School of Engineering.

Construction of the old mess hall was begun in 1897 and completed in 1898 at a cost of $21,000. After the mess hall burned in the early morning hours of November 11, 1911, Bernard Sbisa, steward of the College, served breakfast outdoors at 10 o'clock a.m. The old mess hall was located where McFadden Hall stands now, and was replaced as a dining facility by Sbisa Hall.

The Glasscock Building was built in 1922. Also known as the Agricultural Building, it became home to the History Department in 1996. It is named after Melbern Glasscock, class of 1959, who established the Melbern G. Glasscock Center for Humanities Research at Texas A&M.
Utay Hall was erected in 1939 with 12 other dormitories for a total cost of $2,000,000.

Guion Hall was built in 1918 as an auditorium capable of seating 2500. Construction cost $115,000. It was located at the south end of Military Walk and served as the counterpoint to Sbisa Dining Hall to the north. A well-built structure, it reportedly resisted demolition when it was razed in 1971 to make way for Rudder Tower.
The Aggieland Inn was erected in 1925. This building cost 62,000 dollars. The lower floor was converted to offices for the Basic Division in 1950. The Aggieland Inn was razed in 1966.

Heaton Hall was formerly known as the Exchange Store. This building was erected in 1925 and cost $26,000. After renovation in 1977, it was used by Admissions and Records until they moved to the General Services Complex in 2006.
The first Natatorium was built in 1894 and razed circa 1917.
White Hall was erected in 1939 with 12 other dormitories for a total cost of $2,000,000.
The President's House was originally built in 1965.
The construction for the Academic Building started in 1912 and was finished in 1914. The Academic Building cost 225,000 dollars. The Academic Building was built on the site of Old Main.
The Heep Laboratory was built in 1957. Also known as the "Old Herman Heep Building". Hermann Heep was a member of the Board of Directors from 1957-1960.
This natatorium was built in 1908. The building was converted into a dissecting laboratory in 1916 and razed circa 1933-1937.

Kyle Field was originally erected in 1927. It is named for Edwin Jackson Kyle, class of 1899, who first established a football field on campus in 1904 while chairman of the Athletic Council. Kyle gave a personal note for purchase of lumber and the covered grandstand at the Bryan fairgrounds to equip that earliest football venue.

The Harrington Education Center Office Tower was built in 1973 and the Harrington Education Center Classroom Building in 1974. Named for Marion T. Harrington, class of 1922. Harrington was a former president of Texas A&M (1950-53 and 1957-59) and first chancellor of the Texas A&M System (1953-65).

Krueger and Dunn Halls were erected in 1972. Krueger Hall is named for Carl C. "Polly" Krueger, class of 1912. Krueger was leader of the Ross Volunteers while a student and served as president of the Association of Former Students, a six year term on the universitys Board of Directors, and was a recipient of the Distinguished Alumni Award. Dunn Hall is named for J. Harold Dunn, class of 1925. Dunn served on the Texas A&M Research League, was president of the Amarillo chapter of the Association of Former Students of Texas A&M, and from 1953 to 1959 was a memer of the Texas A&M Board of Regents.
